Below is a **single, self‑contained example** that shows how to expose a C++ `libpcapng`‑style iterator to Python with **pybind11**.  
It contains:

1. **A tiny mock‑implementation** of the C++ library (so you can compile and test the binding without pulling in the real `libpcapng` sources).  
2. **The pybind11 binding code** that turns the C++ iterator into a natural Python iterator and also offers a `for_each(callback)` convenience method that runs a user‑supplied Python callable on every frame.  
3. **Documentation of the Python‑facing API** (what the user will see).  
4. **A minimal Python test script** that shows the intended usage.

> **Why this design?**  
> * The iterator is exposed as a normal Python iterable (`for frame in reader:`) – this is what most Python developers expect.  
> * The extra `for_each(callback)` method lets users apply a piece of code *while* the iterator walks the collection, which is exactly the pattern you asked for.  
> * The binding handles the Global Interpreter Lock (GIL) correctly, releases it while the C++ iterator does I/O work, and reacquires it only when calling back into Python.  
> * All objects are kept alive with `std::shared_ptr` – no dangling references.

---

## 1. The C++ side (mock‑implementation)

```cpp
// file: pcapng_bindings.cpp
// ------------------------------------------------------------
// 1️⃣  Mock libpcapng API (replace with the real headers when you have them)
#include <cstdint>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <memory>
#include <iterator>
#include <fstream>
#include <iostream>

namespace libpcapng {

struct Frame {
    uint64_t timestamp_ns;          // nanoseconds since epoch
    std::vector<uint8_t> data;      // raw packet bytes

    // Convenience helpers (just for the demo)
    std::string to_hex() const {
        static const char* hexdigits = "0123456789ABCDEF";
        std::string out;
        out.reserve(data.size()*2);
        for (auto b : data) {
            out.push_back(hexdigits[b>>4]);
            out.push_back(hexdigits[b&0xF]);
        }
        return out;
    }
};

/// Simple file‑reader that pretends each line is a frame.
class Reader {
public:
    explicit Reader(const std::string& filename) : ifs_(filename) {
        if (!ifs_) throw std::runtime_error("cannot open file: " + filename);
    }

    // -----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 2️⃣  The forward iterator that libpcapng would expose
    class iterator {
    public:
        using iterator_category = std::input_iterator_tag;
        using value_type        = Frame;
        using difference_type   = std::ptrdiff_t;
        using pointer           = const Frame*;
        using reference         = const Frame&;

        iterator() = default;                      // end iterator
        explicit iterator(std::ifstream* ifs) : ifs_(ifs) { ++*this; } // load first

        reference operator*() const { return cur_; }
        pointer   operator->() const { return &cur_; }

        iterator& operator++() {
            std::string line;
            if (!std::getline(*ifs_, line)) { // EOF → become end iterator
                ifs_ = nullptr;
                cur_ = {};
                return *this;
            }
            // Very naive parsing: "timestamp hexbytes"
            std::istringstream iss(line);
            uint64_t ts;
            std::string hex;
            iss >> ts >> hex;
            cur_.timestamp_ns = ts;
            cur_.data.clear();
            for (size_t i = 0; i + 1 < hex.size(); i += 2) {
                unsigned byte;
                std::stringstream ss;
                ss << std::hex << hex.substr(i,2);
                ss >> byte;
                cur_.data.push_back(static_cast<uint8_t>(byte));
            }
            return *this;
        }

        // post‑increment not needed for Python, but nice to have:
        iterator operator++(int) { iterator tmp = *this; ++*this; return tmp; }

        friend bool operator==(const iterator& a, const iterator& b) {
            return a.ifs_ == b.ifs_;
        }
        friend bool operator!=(const iterator& a, const iterator& b) {
            return !(a == b);
        }

    private:
        std::ifstream* ifs_ = nullptr; // nullptr → end iterator
        Frame cur_;
    };
    // -----------------------------------------------------------------

    iterator begin() { return iterator(&ifs_); }
    iterator end()   { return iterator(); }

private:
    std::ifstream ifs_;
};

} // namespace libpcapng
```

> **Note** – The `Reader::iterator` is deliberately simple. In a real binding you would `#include <libpcapng/reader.hpp>` (or whatever the real header is) and expose the *actual* iterator class. The only thing that matters for the binding is that the iterator satisfies the InputIterator concept and that the `value_type` is a copy‑able `Frame`‑like struct.

