## 5️⃣  Plugging the real `libpcapng` library

When you replace the mock implementation with the actual `libpcapng` headers:

```cpp
#include <libpcapng/reader.hpp>   // <-- real header
// keep the same namespace alias (or adjust below)

using Reader   = libpcapng::Reader;
using Frame    = libpcapng::Frame;
using iterator = libpcapng::Reader::iterator;
```

Everything else stays identical – the binding only needs the iterator type and the `Frame` struct to be copy‑constructible (which the real library already provides).

---

## 6️⃣  TL;DR – What you get

| Python construct | C++ behind the scenes | What you can do |
|------------------|----------------------|-----------------|
| `pcapng.Reader(path)` | `libpcapng::Reader` (holds an `std::ifstream`) | Open a capture file |
| `for frame in reader:` | `py::make_iterator(reader.begin(), reader.end())` | Natural Python loop |
| `reader.for_each(callback)` | C++ loop over `reader.begin()/end()` with GIL release | Run arbitrary Python code *while* iterating, with full thread‑friendliness |
| `frame.timestamp_ns`, `frame.data`, `frame.hex` | Direct accessors on `libpcapng::Frame` | Inspect each packet |

You now have a clean, Pythonic API that lets users supply *their own* processing function, while the heavy lifting stays in the fast C++ iterator. 🎉
